ariants":[{"name":"Mal","meanings":["Slovenian: nickname for a physically small man, from <i>mal</i> ‘small, little’.","French (mainly Nord): nickname from <i>mal</i> ‘bad’ (from Latin <i>malus</i>).","Indian (northern states): variant of   Mall  ."]},{"name":"Malette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Alphonse, Francois, Jacques, Rejean, Serge.","French: variant or feminine form of   Malet   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this, reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":7,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":27,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":37,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lord William Malet was born in 1059, in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England as the son of Hesilia Crispin. He married Maud de Mortimer in 1150, in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1130, in his hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1059–1130":"1059–1130","1134–1213":"1134–1213","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","1125":"1125","1213":"1213","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1066":"1066","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1059–1130":"1059–1130","1134–1213":"1134–1213","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","1125":"1125","1213":"1213","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1066":"1066","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1059–1130":"1059–1130","1134–1213":"1134–1213","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1059":"1059","1125":"1125","1213":"1213","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1066":"1066","1220":"122